@article{graumlich03,
   abstract = {Climate variability, coupled with increasing demand
is raising concerns about the sustainability of
water resources in the western United
States. Tree-ring reconstructions of stream flow
that extend the observational record by several
centuries provide critical information on the
short-term variability and multi-decadal trends in
water resources. In this study, precipitation
sensitive Douglas-fir ( Pseudotsuga menzeisii) tree
ring records are used to reconstruct annual flow of
the Yellowstone River back to A. D. 1706. Linkages
between precipitation in the Greater Yellowstone
Region and climate variability in the Pacific basin
were incorporated into our model by including
indices Pacific Ocean interannual and decadal-scale
climatic variability, namely the Pacific Decadal
Oscillation and the Southern Oscillation. The
reconstruction indicates that 20th century
streamflow is not representative of flow during the
previous two centuries. With the exception of the
1930s, streamflow during the 20th century exceeded
average flows during the previous 200 years. The
drought of the 1930s resulted in the lowest flows
during the last three centuries, however, this
probably does not represent a worst-case scenario
