sensitivity of stomatal conductance (g(s)) to soil
moisture below a relative extractable water (REW) of
0.4, and decreased g(s) sensitivity to D-L below REW
of approx. 0.2. This response was captured by the
modified Ball-Berry (Leuning) model. While most
physiological parameters and responses measured were
typical of temperate pines, the
photosynthesis-phenological phasing contributed to
high productivity under warm-dry conditions. This
contrasts with reported effects of short-term
periodical droughts and could lead to different
predictions of the effect of warming and drying
climate on pine forest productivity.},
