@article{gedalof01,
   abstract = {A transect of climate sensitive tree ring-width
chronologies from coastal western North America
provides a useful proxy index of North Pacific
ocean-atmosphere variability since 1600 AD. Here we
use this high-resolution record to identify
intervals of an enhanced interdecadal climate signal
in the North Pacific, and to assess the timing and
magnitude of abrupt shifts in this system. In the
context of this record, the step-like climate shift
that occurred in 1976-1977 is not a unique event,
with similar events having occurred frequently
during the past 400 years. Furthermore, most of the
pre-instrumental portion of this record is
characterized by pronounced interdecadal
variability, while the secular portion is more
strongly interannual in nature. If the 1976-1977
event marks a return to this mode of variability
